Bluetongue virus serotype 14 detected in Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania and Poland
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
During November 2012, Estonia, Latvia, and Lithuania have informed the European Commission on the detection of a significant number of animals, mostly cattle, serologically positive to bluetongue virus. In the 3 countries, the samples were taken in the framework of the bluetongue surveillance. Serologically positive samples were analyzed by RT-PCR and found negative in all cases except in Lithuania where 15 animals showed an equivocal result.

Poland has reported that, similarly within the framework of the bluetongue surveillance, 3 cattle farms have been found to include positive animals both serologically as well by RT-PCR. Furthermore, sequencing was performed leading to the identification of a virus highly compatible with BTV serotype 14. Positive farms are located on the border with Belarus and Lithuania.

All 4 countries have implemented the following measures: animal movement restrictions in the positive farms and epidemiological investigations in the area around them.

All positive samples have been sent to the Community Reference Laboratory (Pirbright) for confirmation and virus sequencing.

It has been recommended to the Veterinary Services of the Autonomous Communities [Spain's administrative regions] to exercise vigilance in relation to animals susceptible to bluetongue which have been imported from the mentioned countries.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[According to the above information, from a Spanish web-site, BTV-14 is suspected in Poland and 3 Baltic countries. Subscribers are referred to an earlier information from Russian sources about an imported calf, suspected in Spain as BTV-14 infected. - Mod.AS]

