Date: Tue 27 Nov 2012
Source: Baltic-Course [edited]
http://www.baltic-course.com/eng/markets_and_companies/?doc=66574


Bluetongue disease can halt Estonian cattle export
--------------------------------------------------
Based on lab studies in Estonia, the Estonian Veterinary and Food Board suspects a beef cattle animal in the Saaremaa island to suffer from bluetongue disease which can cut the export of Estonian cattle considerably if confirmed, LETA/Saarte Haal reports.

"This can turn out to be a very serious setback for Estonian animal farmers," said head of the Animal Breeders Association of Estonia Tanel Bulitko, adding that confirmation of the bluetongue disease will mean export restrictions for Estonia's export to third states, including Turkey and Russia. The prices offered by the Turkish have raised the price of Estonia sheep considerably for other buyers too.

The results of the repeat test conducted in UK should arrive at the end of this week, said Veterinary and Food Board director general Ago Partel, adding that the bluetongue disease has never been diagnosed in Estonia before.

Bluetongue disease or catarrhal fever is a non-infectious insect-borne, viral disease of ruminants, mainly sheep and less frequently cattle. It is caused by the Bluetongue virus (BTV). The virus is transmitted by the midge Culicoides imicola and other culicoids. In sheep, BTV causes an acute disease with high morbidity and mortality.

[Byline: Juhan Tere]

